# Structured Outputs
## What are they?
Structured outputs refer to making AI models return responses in a predictable, machine-readable format (like JSON or XML) rather than free-form prose.
## Why It Matters?
When you're building applications, you don't want the AI to say "Sure! Here are the results..." — you want clean data you can immediately use in your code. Structured outputs solve this.
## How It Works?
Without structured outputs:
User: Extract the name and age from this text: "John is 30 years old."
AI: "The name is John and the age is 30."
You'd have to parse that sentence yourself — fragile and error-prone.

With structured outputs:
json{ "name": "John", "age": 30 }
Ready to use directly in your app.

## Common Techniques
1. Prompt-based — You instruct the model in your prompt:
"Respond only in JSON with keys: name, age. No extra text."
Simple but unreliable; the model might still add prose.

2. JSON Schema / Response Format — APIs like OpenAI and Anthropic let you pass a schema the model must conform to. The output is guaranteed to match your structure.

3. Tool/Function Calling — You define a "function" with typed parameters, and the model fills them in. This is the most robust method and works well for agents.

## Use Cases
Use Case
Example 
Output
[Data extraction: Pull fields from documents or emails
Classification { "sentiment": "positive", "confidence": 0.92 }]

[Form filling: Populate structured records from free text
Agent actions Model decides which tool to call and with what args
API responses Power a backend endpoint with AI-generated data]

In the Anthropic API specifically
You can use tool use (function calling) to get structured outputs. You define a tool with an input schema, and Claude will call it with structured arguments:
javascripttools: [{
  name: "extract_person",
  input_schema: {
    type: "object",
    properties: {
      name: { type: "string" },
      age:  { type: "integer" }
    },
    required: ["name", "age"]
  }
}]
Claude will respond with a tool_use block containing valid, typed JSON matching your schema — no parsing guesswork needed.

## Key Benefits
Reliability — No more regex-ing AI responses
Type safety — Know exactly what fields and types to expect
Composability — Chain AI outputs directly into other systems
Validation — Schemas enforce constraints (required fields, enums, ranges)

Structured outputs are fundamental to building robust, production-grade AI applications. 